{"type":"message","id":"0228c0c4","parentId":"82845b16","timestamp":"2026-05-15T07:43:14.796Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! There's a WebException at line 350661: `The remote server returned an error: (404) Not Found.` This was during the earlier run (the log from 12:40). But this is from the first run's log, not related to our current execution.\n\nThe second Unity process (PID 23816) was for a different build target. It wrote its output to the BuildPipeline_RunHotUpdate.log starting from the old log content and then the log stopped at 15:34:26 with SpriteAtlasPacking completed entries.\n\nWait, actually, I need to re-think this. The first Unity run (PID 17676 at 15:20:56) was writing to BuildPipeline_RunHotUpdate.log. It ran through Lua merge, and then presumably compiled and started building asset bundles. The log had grown to 37MB.\n\nThen PID 23816 started at 15:34:31. This was a new Unity process, but it was also writing to the same log file. The log last write shows 15:34:26, and PID 23816 started at 15:34:31. So PID 23816 started AFTER the log was last updated.\n\nWait, let me think about this differently. Maybe PID 23816 was NOT spawned by the bat file. Maybe it was a Unity Editor that was already open when the bat ran, and the bat file's Unity process (PID 17676) actually completed on its own. Let me check.\n\nActually, I think what happened is:\n1. First Unity process (17676) ran the pipeline starting at 15:20:56\n2. It completed the first stage (Lua merge, etc.) and then at some point it exited\n3. Then the bat file's first Unity process completed and the bat started a SECOND Unity process for the next stage (which is actually a separate -executeMethod call for building bundles)\n4. OR, even more likely: the bat file ran Unity, it completed the pipeline, and then something else launched a new Unity editor instance\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. Let me just look at very specific things. The bat file says to run Unity with `-batchmode -quit`. Unity runs the `RunHotUpdatePipeline` method. This method likely builds asset bundles and uploads to CDN, then Unity exits. Unity exited successfully (it says \"Cleanup mono\" in the log).\n\nBut the BuildPipeline_RunHotUpdate.log didn't record the full output. This could be because:\n- The log file got too large (it was already 37MB from the previous run's log) and Unity truncated it\n- OR the log was from the old run and the new run's output is being buffered\n\nWait - looking back at my exec results, I used `Start-Process -RedirectStandardOutput` which means the bat file ran, and the first Unity process (17676) ran and wrote to the log. When Unity restarted for the next stage (23816), it was launched by the bat file's exit handler or by the pipeline itself. But PID 23816 used the same log file.\n\nActually, I think the pipeline might use multiple Unity invocations for different targets (like Android, iOS, etc.), and each invocation writes to the same log file. PID 23816 was the second invocation but it seems to have crashed or been killed prematurely.\n\nLet me check if maybe PID 23816 was launched by something else entirely. Let me check the Unity processes more carefully and search for error messages.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_3HIQ8Tb4pPGJcnxeGzVu1907","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Select-String -Path \"E:\\Solo\\nightoffullmoon\\client\\cardv\\BuildPipeline_RunHotUpdate.log\" -Pattern \"BuildPipeline|HotUpdate|热更|CDN|Upload|upload|Success|success|Completed|completed\" -CaseSensitive:$false | Select-Object -Last 20"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":860,"output":853,"cacheRead":29696,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":31409,"cost":{"input":0.00012040000000000001,"output":0.00023884,"cacheRead":0.000831488,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.001190728}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778830982016,"respons