{"type":"message","id":"1c38717d","parentId":"5ef1362f","timestamp":"2026-05-15T07:45:09.258Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Editor.log shows \"Cleanup mono\" and licensing cleanup, which means Unity exited cleanly from the Editor.log perspective. But this Editor.log seems to be from a different Unity session (it shows GUI performance entries like \"GameView.KeyUp\", \"InspectorWindow.MouseDown\"), so this is from the Unity Editor GUI, not the batchmode session.\n\nThe batchmode Unity process (which wrote to BuildPipeline_RunHotUpdate.log) doesn't write to Editor.log; it writes to the log file specified by `-logFile`. So the Editor.log is irrelevant here.\n\nI think what happened is:\n1. Unity batchmode ran the pipeline\n2. The pipeline got to the BuildAssetBundles step\n3. During SpriteAtlasPacking, it was building texture atlases\n4. Something caused Unity to exit (either crash without writing to log, or was killed)\n5. The log file stops mid-stream at line 359,704 with SpriteAtlasPacking\n\nBut wait - I also saw PID 23816 start at 15:34:31. Let me check if that was a new Unity batchmode process or something else.\n\nActually, let me just check the Unity processes now:","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_Vb2aRnXGwaLQULtqgbUm5039","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-Process -Name \"Unity\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Select-Object Id, StartTime, CPU, CommandLine; Get-CimInstance Win32_Process -Filter \"Name='Unity.exe'\" | Select-Object ProcessId, CommandLine, CreationDate"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":569,"output":350,"cacheRead":41600,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42519,"cost":{"input":0.00007966,"output":0.00009800000000000001,"cacheRead":0.0011648,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.00134246}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778831101837,"responseId":"e5356927-8144-4194-9e4a-8886610ea09a"}}
