{"type":"message","id":"011b6525","parentId":"73d4c938","timestamp":"2026-05-15T08:33:31.090Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still the same - the log wasn't updated. The bat file ran but Unity immediately exited because of the license issue.\n\nThe fundamental problem is that the Unity Editor license needs to be re-authenticated. The user needs to log in to Unity Hub to renew the authentication token. \n\nLet me check if we can use the `--activateSession` parameter of the licensing client to start a new session.\n\nActually, I just realized something. The earlier successful run (at 15:20) used the Hub's licensing client. But the current failing run is using the editor's bundled licensing client. The issue is that the editor's version 1.12.1 bundled client is different from the Hub's version 1.13.1.\n\nWhen Unity starts in batchmode, it checks the license. The bundled licensing client tries to load the ULF file from `C:\\ProgramData\\Unity\\Unity_lic.ulf`. I deleted this file, but Unity still says \"Cannot load ULF license\". This might be because Unity's code is trying to check if there's a license, and the bundled client can't create a new one without credentials.\n\nLet me try a different approach: use the Hub's licensing client to create a license session, then run Unity.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_uoE7D7xFZy6EEinx1Gpb0539","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Try to create an activation session using the Hub's licensing client\n& \"C:\\Program Files\\Unity Hub\\UnityLicensingClient_V1\\Unity.Licensing.Client.exe\" --activateSession 2>&1","timeout":30}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":473,"output":361,"cacheRead":52352,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":53186,"cost":{"input":0.00006622,"output":0.00010108,"cacheRead":0.001465856,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.001633156}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778834005468,"r