{"type":"message","id":"d0971c0c","parentId":"23772037","timestamp":"2026-05-15T08:37:24.288Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There IS a Unity process running! PID 16220, started at 16:36:49, with 3.5GB working set. This Unity instance has the project open, which is why the batchmode Unity complained \"Multiple Unity instances cannot open the same project.\"\n\nThis Unity instance was started by the GUI mode test earlier (when I ran `Start-Process -FilePath $unity -ArgumentList \"-projectPath...\"`). It started Unity in GUI mode but minimized, and then I killed the process after 30 seconds with `$p.Kill()`... but apparently it spawned a child process that didn't get killed!\n\nThe original PID I killed was 13664, but PID 16220 is a different process (started at 16:36:49, which is after I killed the first one). \n\nWait - actually, the crash report is from 16:37:08 which is the batchmode Unity that crashed. PID 16220 started at 16:36:49 which... hmm, that's between the GUI test (16:35:20) and the current batchmode run (16:37:08).\n\nI think what happened is:\n1. The GUI test at 16:35:20 started Unity (PID 13664) - I killed it at 16:35:50\n2. But Unity Hub might have automatically reopened the project, starting PID 16220 at 16:36:49\n3. Then my batchmode attempt at 16:37 failed because PID 16220 had the project open\n\nLet me kill this Unity process and try again.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_gULfzJCh9GEaAH3xe7gl3540","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Kill the Unity editor that's holding the project\nWrite-Host \"Killing Unity PID 16220...\"\nStop-Process -Id 16220 -Force -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue\nStart-Sleep -Seconds 5\n\n# Verify it's gone\nGet-Process -Name \"Unity\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Select-Object Id, StartTime\nWrite-Host \"---\"\nWrite-Host \"Unity processes after kill:\"\nif (Get-Process -Name \"Unity\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue) { \"Still running